the planning of the American-funded Turkish highway network, and the development of the Turkish tourism industry, Adalet also highlights how "problems of knowledge" are fundamentally entwined with "problems of the political order": social scientific theories are produced in material spaces, through uncertain encounters between transnational actors and policy networks. In tracking the growth and transmission of modernization as a theory and in practice in Turkey, Hotels and Highways offers not only a specific history of a postwar development model that continues to influence our world, but a widely relevant consideration of how theoretical debates take shape in concrete situations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aEconomic assistance, AmericanzTurkeyxHistoryy20th century. 0aEconomic developmentzTurkeyxHistoryy20th century. 0aSocial changezTurkeyxHistoryy20th century. 0aSocial scienceszUnited StatesxPhilosophyxHistoryy20th century. 4aCold War. 4aDankwart Rustow. 4aDevelopment. 4aHighways. 4aHotels. 4aInfrastructure. 4aModernization Theory. 4aSurvey Research. 4aTourism. 4aU.S.-Turkey. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Turkey & Ottoman Empire.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311070368940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360555840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503605558423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503605558.jpg  a978-3-11-070368-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles